ber 5, 2012|date=August 22, 2012}}</ref> \n*[[Juan Diego Fl\u00f3rez]]  ([[Live 8]] \u2013 Berlin) (2005)\n*[[Judy Garland]] (1960)<ref>[http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm Recorded for Capitol Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430042453/http://www.jgdb.com/capstud.htm |date=April 30, 2008 }} Judy Garland with Orchestra conducted, by Norrie Paramor, August 3, 1960.</ref>\n*[[Katherine Jenkins]] (2005)\n*[[Keith Jack]] (2008)\n*[[Kevin Rowland]] (1999)\n*[[Kiri Te Kanawa]] with the [[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1990) \u2013 ''Songs of Inspiration''\n*[[The Knickerbockers]] (1966)\n*[[Lee Greenwood]]\n*[[Lee Towers]] (1976)<ref>[https://www.leetowers.nl/index.php/discografie-mainmenu-110 It's Raining In My Heart] (LP/MC) (Goud & Platina) 1976</ref>\n*[[The Lettermen]] (1964)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |title=You'll Never Walk Alone |publisher=Thelettermen.com |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717011801/http://www.thelettermen.com/1960.html |archivedate=July 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Tammy Wynette]] (1969 Inspiration)\n*[[Liverpool F.C.]] (1977)  (FA Cup single: A-side - \"We Can Do It\" / \"Liverpool Lou\"  B-side - \"We Shall Not Be Moved\" / \"You'll Never Walk Alone\")\n*[[Los Fastidios]]\n*[[Louis Armstrong]] (1954) in a medley with [[Tenderly]]\n*[[Mahalia Jackson]]\n*[[Malena Ernman]] (2013)\n*[[Malcolm Vaughan]] (1959)\n*[[Marcus Mumford]] (2020)\n*[[Mark Knopfler]] (2018) incorporated an instrumental version into the track Just a Boy Away From Home on his album [[Down the Road Wherever]]\n*[[Mark Vincent]] (2010)\n*[[Mario Lanza]] (1952 and 1956)\n*[[Maureen Forrester]] on the Carousel MCA Classics album (1987)\n*[[Melanie C|Melanie Chisholm]] (2012)\n*[[Michael Crawford]] (1987)\n*[[Mormon Tabernacle Choir]] (1971)\n*[[Nina Simone]] (1958, ''[[Little Girl Blue (album)|Little Girl Blue]]'')\n*[[Olivia Newton-John]] (1989) \u2013 ''[[Warm and Tender (Olivia Newton-John album)|Warm and Tender]]''\n*[[Patricia Neway]] in the soundtrack of the 1967 television adaptation of ''Carousel'' (1967)\n*[[Patti Labelle & The Blue Belles]] (1964) - US #34\n*[[Patti LaBelle]] (1980's)\n*[[Pink Floyd]] (1971) \u2013 \"[[Fearless (Pink Floyd song)|Fearless]]\"\n*[[Pips, Chips & Videoclips]] (''[[Dernjava]]'' album, 1995)\n*[[The Priests]] (2009)\n*[[Perry Como]] (1951) (with Mitchell Ayres Orchestra)\n*[[Ray Charles]] (''[[Ingredients in a Recipe for Soul]]'' album track, July 1963)\n*[[Regine Velasquez]] (1989)\n*[[Ren\u00e9e Fleming]] (2003)\n*[[The Righteous Brothers]] (1965)\n*[[Riverdale Cast]] featuring main vocals of [[Madelaine Petsch]] (2018), appeared on ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' <ref>https://genius.com/Riverdale-cast-youll-never-walk-alone-lyrics</ref>\n*[[Robin S]] (appears on the 1998 movie soundtrack, ''[[Welcome to Woop Woop]]'')\n*[[Robson & Jerome]] (1996)\n*[[Roy Hamilton]] (1954)<ref name=pc3/>\n*[[Roy Orbison]] (1969) [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] (2015) Released\n*[[Samuel Ramey]] (1989)\n*[[Sergio Franchi]] recorded on 1964 RCA album, ''The Exciting Voice of Sergio Franchi''\n*[[The Shadows]] (''[[Reflection (The Shadows album)|Reflection]]'' album track, 1990)\n*[[Shirley Bassey]] (1962, single B-side to \"Ave Maria\")<ref>''Columbia Catalog Number DB4816\"</ref>\n*[[Shirley Jones]] recorded it on the original movie soundtrack of ''Carousel'' and again on her 1989 album ''[[Silent Strength]]''\n*[[Sissel Kyrkjeb\u00f8]] (2004)\n*[[Smoking Popes]]\n*[[The Soldiers]] (2011)\n*[[Steven Houghton]] (1997) \u2013 ''Steven Houghton''\n*[[Susan Boyle]] (''[[Standing Ovation: The Greatest Songs from the Stage]]'', 2012)\n* Tape Toy (''[[2019-20 Coronavirus outbreak]]'', 2020)\n*[[The Three Tenors]] (''[[The Three Tenors: Paris 1998]]'', 1998)\n*[[Tokyo Ska Paradise Orchestra]] (2009) \u2013 ''Paradise Blue''\n*[[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] (1969)\n*[[Trisha Yearwood]] (2016) - ''[[The Passion (U.S. TV special)|The Passion]]''\n*[[Vocal Majority]] (1997) \u2013 ''How Sweet the Sound''\n*[[Wayne Hussey]] and [[Julianne Regan]] (as [[Hussey-Regan]]) (2011) (in support of Liverpool F.C.'s disability charity, [[Respect 4 All]])<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/liverpoolfc#p/u/13/xy8MPNixmgI \"You'll Never Walk Alone\"]. Youtube.com (Liverpool FC's Channel). Retrieved December 27, 2011.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|barbra-streisand|youll-never-walk-alone}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Rodgers and Hammerstein}}\n{{Liverpool F.C.}}\n{{Liliom}}\n{{Roy Hamilton}}\n{{The Bachelors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:You'll Never Walk Alone}}\n[[Category:1945 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rodgers and Hammerstein musicals]]\n[[Category:Shirley Jones songs]]\n[[Category:Gerry and the Pacemakers songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Labelle songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Jane Morgan songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Preston songs]]\n[[Category:Glen Campbell songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Feyenoord songs]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. songs]]\n[[Category:Charity singles]]\n[[Category:Football songs and chants]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Mahalia Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Roy Hamilton songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Graphophone Company singles]]\n[[Category:Laurie Records singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You%27ll_Never_Walk_Alone"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Chong", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian-American comedian, actor, and activist}}\n<!--Note:  There is an internet hoax reporting Chong's death.  http://en.mediamass.net/people/tommy-chong/deathhoax.html-->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name         = Tommy Chong\n| image        = Tommy_Chong_at_Hash_Bash.jpg\n| caption      = Chong in 2015\n| birth_name   = Thomas Bee Kin Chong\n| nationality  = Canadian, American\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1938|5|24}}  \n| birth_place  = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| medium       = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[film]], [[television]]\n| genre        =  [[Observational comedy]], [[stoner comedy]], [[sketch comedy]], [[satire]]\n| subject      = [[Canadian culture]], [[recreational drug use]], [[drug culture]], [[everyday life]]\n| active       = 1962\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Maxine Sneed|1960|1970|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]]|1975}}\n| children     = 5, including [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]], [[Robbi Chong|Robbi]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Bing Kin Chong'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |website=Post Gazette |title=Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes |date=September 12, 2003 |access-date=August 10, 2016 |last=Ove |first=Torsten |publisher=PG Publishing Co., Inc. |quote=Chong, whose full name is Thomas B. Kin Chong,... |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716002912/http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |archivedate=July 16, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> (born May 24, 1938) is a Canadian-American actor, writer, director, musician, [[cannabis rights]] activist and comedian. He is known for his [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]-themed [[Cheech & Chong]] comedy albums and movies with [[Cheech Marin]], as well as playing the character [[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]] on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[That '70s Show]]''. He became a naturalized United States citizen in the late 1980s.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas B. Kin Chong<ref name= \"nardwuar\">{{cite web |date=August 20, 1993|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bGhBodZP1Jw|title=Nardwuar vs. Tommy Chong|work=Nardwuar | via=YouTube |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cheechandchong.com/biography.html | title= Bio > Tommy Chong| work= CheechandChong.com (official site)| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120213175242/http://www.cheechandchong.com/bio | archivedate= February 13, 2012}} Note: Tommy Chong bio appears under a different person's section, Shelby Chong.</ref> was born on May 24, 1938 at the [[University of Alberta Hospital]] in [[Edmonton]], Alberta.<ref name=filmref /> His mother was Lorna Jean (n\u00e9e Gilchrist),<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/18/Tommy-Chong.html | title=Tommy Chong Biography (1938-)| website= FilmReference.com | accessdate= June 17, 2015}}</ref> a waitress of [[Scottish- Canadians|Scottish-Irish]] ancestry,<ref>{{cite news |title= [Unknown title] |volume= 80 |year=1972 |work= [[Newsweek]] |location=|isbn= |page= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=d03uAAAAMAAJ&q=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH&dq=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> and his father was Stanley Chong, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] truck driver who [[Chinese Canadians|immigrated to Canada]] in the 1930s.<ref name= filmref /><ref name=\"asianweek\"/> After arriving in Canada, the senior Chong had first lived with an aunt in [[Vancouver]], where Chinese immigrants were mostly sequestered in a small area due to racial discrimination.<ref name=\"asianweek\">{{cite news | first=Pratt | last=Paul | title=Growing Up a Chong | date=November 18, 2005 | work=AsianWeek | url=http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609190311/http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | archivedate=June 9, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=7072|title= Working to Reform Marijuana Laws | website= NORML.org |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/thomas-chong/contributor/264446|title=Tommy Chong|work=Yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\nAs a youth, Tommy Chong moved with his family to [[Calgary]], settling in a conservative neighbourhood Chong has referred to as \"Dog Patch\". He has said that his father had \"been wounded in [[World War II]] and there was a veterans' hospital in Calgary. He bought a $500 house in Dog Patch and raised his family on $50 a week.\"<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/> In an interview, Chong later said:\n{{cquote|I dropped out of [[Crescent Heights High School (Calgary, Alberta)|Crescent Heights High School]] when I was 16 but probably just before they were going to throw me out anyway&nbsp;... I played guitar to make money. I was about 16 when I discovered that music could get you [[sexual intercourse|laid]], even if you were a scrawny, long-haired, geeky-looking guy like me.<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/>}}\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nBy the early 1960s, Chong was playing guitar for a Calgary soul group called the Shades. The Shades moved to [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], where the band's name changed to \"Little Daddy & the Bachelors\". They recorded a single, \"Too Much Monkey Business\" / \"Junior's Jerk\". Together with bandmember Bobby Taylor, Chong opened a Vancouver nightclub in 1963.  Formerly the Alma Theatre, they called it \"Blue Balls\". They brought in the [[Ike & Tina Turner]] Revue, which had never been to Vancouver before. Although Little Daddy & the Bachelors built up a small following, things soured when they went with Chong's suggestion and had themselves billed as \"Four [[Nigger]]s and a [[Chink]]\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|author=Hamilton, Andrew|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p130602|title=Bobby Taylor|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> (or, bowing to pressure, \"Four N's and a C\") before taking on the moniker [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n\nIn 1965, the Vancouvers signed with Gordy Records (a subsidiary of Detroit's [[Motown Records]]). They recorded their debut album, an [[eponymous]] release, and their debut single, the Tommy Chong co-composition, \"Does Your Mama Know About Me,\" which peaked at number 29 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> While on tour in Chicago for a short time, the band followed opening act [[the Jackson 5]]. Chong later referred to the young [[Michael Jackson]] as a \"cute little guy\".<ref name=\"tomgreen.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tomgreen.com/?video=1089|title=Tom Green - The Channel - WebovisionTom Green - The Channel|publisher=}}</ref> After the band released two additional singles, Chong and bandmate Wes Henderson missed a Friday night performance to apply for [[Permanent residence (United States)|green cards]] so they could become American citizens. Chong was fired by [[Chris Clark (singer)|Chris Clark]] and Motown producer [[Johnny Bristol]] for arriving late to the gig. Later, when Berry Gordy told Chong that he wasn't fired after all, that it had been a mistake, Chong said he wanted to stay fired. \"I said I want to become a Berry Gordy, I don't want to just work for a Berry Gordy. And he says I can, I can dig that. So he was nice. He gave me $5,000 as the severance and to me that was a fortune.\" - Tommy Chong. <!--Above material apparently had been copied from article \"Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers\"--><ref name=\"harp\">{{cite web\n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |last=Kayce \n |first=Aaron \n |title=Tommy Chong: From Guitar to Bong \n |work=Harp \n |publisher=HarpMagazine.com \n |accessdate=September 24, 2007 \n |url-status=bot: unknown \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425165739/http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |archivedate=April 25, 2009 \n}}</ref> The group broke up shortly afterwards, when Chong tried to reduce the number of players covered by the Vancouvers' contract. He intended that he, Taylor, and Henderson would constitute the group, while other members would be classified as sidemen and session artists.\n\n===Cheech & Chong===\n{{Main|Cheech & Chong}}\nChong co-wrote and performed on many Cheech & Chong comedy albums, four of which were nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]. He and [[Cheech Marin]] shared the 1973 award in this category for ''[[Los Cochinos]]''.<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22cheech+and+chong%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All Cheech and Chong at grammy.com]</ref>\n\nHe also directed four of the duo's films, while co-writing and starring in all seven with Cheech.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Tommy Chong|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/person/683301/Tommy-Chong/filmography}}</ref>\n\n===After Cheech & Chong===\n[[File:Tommy Chong in 2008.jpg|thumb|Chong speaking in San Francisco in 2008.]]\nCheech & Chong, while a very successful comedy act, split in 1985 due to creative differences and Marin's desire to focus on a mainstream acting career. This began a difficult time for Chong. He developed an unsold pilot for CBS called ''The Martinez Family'', which was redeveloped as the 1988 sitcom ''[[Trial and Error (TV series)|Trial and Error]]''.<ref name=\"Irvin2013\">{{cite book|author=Richard Irvin|title=Forgotten Laughs: An Episode Guide to 150 TV Sitcoms You Probably Never Saw|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqRWDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276|year=2013|publisher=BearManor Media|pages=276\u2013|id=GGKEY:Y33N3H4NXN4}}</ref> In 1990, he directed, wrote and starred in the movie ''[[Far Out Man]]''. He did not act regularly until filling the recurring role (later a regular role) as the fun-loving, aging hippie \"[[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]]\" (similar to his Chong character) on ''[[That '70s Show]]''. Chong was absent during the fifth and sixth seasons of the show as he was serving a brief jail sentence; upon his release, he returned to the series for its final two seasons. He also played a role as a hippie in ''[[Dharma and Greg]]''.\n\nChong was originally going to voice the character of [[Shenzi, Banzai and Ed|Shenzi]], the hyena in the Disney film ''[[The Lion King]]''.{{citation needed| date=May 2018}} Cheech Marin voiced Banzai. (The Shenzi character was changed to a female, and voiced instead by [[Whoopi Goldberg]].) Chong provided the voice of the character Yax in the 2016 Disney film ''[[Zootopia]]''.<ref name=\"USA Today 25 October 2015\">{{cite news | title= J.K. Simmons, Tommy Chong get run of 'Zootopia'|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/25/zootopia-jk-simmons-tommy-chong/74369682/| last= Alexander | first= Bryan | date=October 25, 2015| work= USA Today |publisher= [[Gannett Company]]| accessdate= May 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2005, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. The documentary, produced, written and directed by Josh Gilbert, chronicles Chong's comedic and personal history. It includes material related to his prosecution by the [[United States Department of Justice|US Justice Department]] and imprisonment. The project features interviews with Cheech Marin, [[Bill Maher]], [[George Thorogood]], [[Peter Coyote]], [[Lou Adler]], [[Eric Schlosser]] and [[Jay Leno]]. In 2011, Chong appeared as a Judge in an episode of ''[[Franklin & Bash]].''\n\nOn September 4, 2014, Chong was announced as one of the celebrities participating on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|19th season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He paired with professional dancer [[Peta Murgatroyd]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Dancing With The Stars': Season 19 Celebrity Contestants Revealed|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/09/04/dancing-with-the-stars-season-19-cast-dwts-celebrities/|publisher=Hollywood Life}}</ref> Despite being at the bottom of the leaderboard numerous times, Chong and Murgatroyd were able to make it to the night of the semi-finals but were eliminated at the end of that night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|title='Dancing with the Stars' Recap: Top 5 in the Semifinals|access-date=November 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121103908/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|archive-date=November 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Chong is the oldest contestant to have made it to the semi-finals of the show.\n\nOn April 4, 2015, Chong appeared as a guest speaker at the annual \"Hash Bash\" event in Ann Arbor, Michigan, which focuses on cannabis legalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F23Bwk-he8o|title='Hash Bash, 2015'|publisher=GrowGreenerGuru}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Chong guest-starred as himself in an episode of the ''[[Trailer Park Boys]]'' spinoff ''Out of the Park: USA''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5937754/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title='Trailer Park Boys: Out of the Park'|publisher=IMDB}}</ref> In 2017, Chong also partnered with smoking subscription box service Daily High Club to create the DHC Tommy Chong Signature Smoking Supply Box.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.investorideas.com/news/2017/marijuana/11021TommyChong.asp|title='Daily High Club Announces Partnership with Cannabis Culture Legend Tommy Chong'|publisher=Investorideas.com|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2019 he was revealed at the end of the second episode of ''[[The Masked Singer (U.S. TV series)]]'' to be the singer known as the Pineapple, singing \"[[I Will Survive]]\" by [[Gloria Gaynor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/a25832138/masked-singer-revealed-season-1/|title=Find Out Who Was Unmasked This Week on 'The Masked Singer'|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|date=2019-01-09|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #1303 of the internet video podcast ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'', hosted by [[Joe Rogan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4rHLLmQPqLY|title=Joe Rogan Experience #1303 - Tommy Chong|date=2019-05-23|website=YouTube|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #694 of the internet video podcast \"The Church Of What's Happening Now\", hosted by [[Joey Diaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kVwm0uKPRVs|title='TCOWHN: #694 - Tommy Chong'|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Cheech & Chong among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\n===''US vs. Chong''===\nIn 2003 Chong became caught up in two American investigations, code-named [[Operation Pipe Dreams]] and [[Operation Headhunter]], which tried to trace drug traffic and users through businesses selling [[drug paraphernalia]], mostly [[bong]]s.  Operation Pipe Dreams was run from [[Pittsburgh]]. US Attorney for [[Western Pennsylvania]] [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] oversaw the case. The estimated cost of Operation Pipe Dreams was over $12 million and included the resources of 2,000 law enforcement officers.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Mikulan|title=Chong Family Values|date=December 4, 2003|publisher=LA Weekly Times|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127205521/http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 27, 2013}}</ref> Fifty-five companies that sold drug paraphernalia over the Internet were the subject of the investigation, and Nice Dreams was one of them.\n\nChong was charged for his part in financing and promoting Chong Glass/Nice Dreams, a company started by his son Paris. His case never went to trial, as his attorney negotiated a plea agreement with the US Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania's Office. He admitted to distributing 7,500 bongs and water pipes on the Internet through Nice Dreams, a family company. Chong agreed to plead guilty to one count of conspiracy to distribute drug paraphernalia in exchange for non-prosecution of his wife, Shelby, and his son, Paris. Chong cooperated with the government and was the first of the Operation Pipe Dreams defendants to plead guilty.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nAt Chong's sentencing, Assistant U.S. Attorney for Western Pennsylvania Mary McKeen Houghton said in her arguments that Tommy Chong \"used his public image to promote this crime\" and marketed his products to children.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite news |author=Torsten Ove | title=Chong Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes| date=September 13, 2003 | newspaper= Pittsburgh Post Gazette| url= http://www.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp}}</ref> U.S. Attorney [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] also was present at the sentencing in Pittsburgh and released a statement to the press stating, \"there are consequences for violating the law, even if the violator is a well-known entertainer like Thomas Chong.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nWhile Chong argued for community service and home detention at his sentencing, the district judge, [[Arthur J. Schwab]], denied his requests and sentenced him to 9 months in federal prison, a fine of $20,000, forfeiture of $103,514, and the loss of all merchandise seized during the raid of his business.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\" /> Chong served his sentence at the [[Taft Correctional Institution]] from October 8, 2003 to July 7, 2004. He was a cellmate\u2014or \"cubie\"\u2014with \"The Wolf of Wall Street\" [[Jordan Belfort]], and is given credit for encouraging Belfort to write his memoirs. They have remained friends ever since.<ref name=NYMag>{{cite journal|last=Gray|first=Geoffrey|title=The Wolf of Wall Street Can't Sleep|journal=New York|date=December 2, 2013|year=|pages=64\u201369|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/jordan-belfort-2013-12/|accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThese events were among those chronicled in ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' (2006), a documentary by [[Josh Gilbert (filmmaker)|Josh Gilbert]]. It premiered theatrically at the New York Film Forum in New York City and won awards. His time in prison was also a main point in his book, \"The I Chong\".\n\n===Controversy===\n[[File:Tommy Chong by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Chong in 2006]]\nWhile government officials denied that Chong was treated any differently from the other defendants, supporters felt his celebrity status was being used against him. Chong's publicist [[Brandie Knight]] said the Chong family was shocked by the raid. \"We've done everything the right way, and the government is saying there is no right way,\" Knight said.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. raids firms selling items used by pot smokers / Ashcroft blames Internet for paraphernalia|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs/2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301163234/http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs|archivedate=March 1, 2011| newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> Supporters started the \"Free Tommy Chong!\" movement that called for his release. They questioned why Chong was prosecuted rather than his son Paris Chong, who was CEO of the business. They also pointed to the disparity in sentences between Chong's and those of other defendants and the DEA tactics used in the investigation.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nParis Chong had started Nice Dreams in 1999. He was never charged with his crimes in relation to the investigation as part of a plea bargain. When asked why the government had focused on Chong rather than his son the CEO, US Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan said that \"Tommy Chong was the more responsible corporate officer because he financed and marketed the product.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nOf the 55 people who were subjects of the investigation, Chong was the only one without previous convictions who received jail time.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> When questioned on the sentencing, U.S. Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan noted that Chong had never gone to trial and made a plea bargain. She said, \"He was a relatively new player, but he had the ability to market products like no other.\"<ref name=\"Tommy Chong's Bongs\">{{cite magazine |author=Greg Beato | title=Tommy Chong's Bongs| date=May 2004 | magazine= Reason Magazine| url= http://www.reason.com/news/show/29137.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring its investigation of Nice Dreams, federal agents posed as head-shop owners from [[Beaver County, Pennsylvania|Beaver County]] in western Pennsylvania. They asked Paris Chong to sell them [[Water pipe percolator|pipes]] through the mail to a fictitious shop in the town of [[Beaver Falls, Pennsylvania|Beaver Falls]], {{convert|31|mi|km}} from Pittsburgh. Paris Chong had been prohibited from selling to Pittsburgh or anywhere in [[Western Pennsylvania]] because of the successful federal prosecution of Akhil Kumar Mishra and his wife, Rajeshwari, who had two head shops in the city.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Accounts differ as to who in Nice Dreams went against Chong's prohibition, or even if it had been made up by the defense, but the sales did take place to the agents. This enabled the U.S. Attorney to show jurisdiction in Pennsylvania for Chong's illegal activities, as opposed to California, which was the base for Nice Dreams.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===Aftermath===\nIn December 2004, Chong was to appear in an off-Broadway show entitled ''[[The Marijuana-Logues]]'', a parody of [[Eve Ensler]]'s ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]''. His parole officer barred him from the show and the tour was cancelled, as audience members were smoking pot during performances. Such exposure would cause Chong to violate the terms of his parole.<ref name=\"The Marijuana-Logues up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour'\">{{cite news|author=Jake Coyle|title=\"The Marijuana-Logues\" up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour |date=February 28, 2005 |newspaper=The Seattle Times|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002192319_webchong28.html}}</ref> In 2006, Chong published a memoir about his experiences in jail and his exploration of meditation, called ''The I Chong: Meditations from the Joint''.\n\nIn 2010, Chong and [[Cyril Wecht]] appeared at a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] fundraiser in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] to aid the campaign against [[Mary Beth Buchanan]], the [[United States Attorney]] who prosecuted him. She was running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Roddy |first=Dennis B. |title=Chong and Wecht form an unlikely alliance against Buchanan |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=May 6, 2010 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10126/1056036-53.stm#ixzz0n7uLO400 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> She was defeated in the Republican primary.\n\n===Seizure of a/k/a Tommy Chong DVDs===\nOn May 7, 2008, federal agents raided Spectrum Labs in an investigation related to its \"detoxification\" products. The search was one of nine conducted for [[Operation True Test]], an investigation being led by Buchanan, still the U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania. It targeted companies that sell so-called \"masking products,\" intended to help drug-users pass employer drug tests. No federal law bans such products; they are regulated on a state-by-state basis. Of the nine search warrants issued, none was for businesses within Buchanan's district.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |author=Paula Reed Ward |title=Buchanan picks new target: products that mask drug use |date=May 11, 2008 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post Gazette |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08132/880918-52.stm}}</ref>\n\nChong claimed that federal agents had seized 8,000\u201310,000 copies of the yet-to-be released documentary, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]],'' from Spectrum Labs, but their attorney said no DVDs were taken.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In a press release, Chong said, \"[The seizure of the DVDs is] a way to punish the distributor financially. There's no way to get the DVDs back until the investigation is over.\" Chong said he did not have any ownership of the film.<ref name=\"raid\">{{cite news| title=Actor Tommy Chong Claims Link to FBI Raids| date=May 8, 2008| publisher=Local 12.com| url=http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512153035/http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| archivedate=May 12, 2008| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' later amended its story, saying that an \"undisclosed number of DVDs was taken\". It noted the government is not required to disclose a reason for the seizure as the raid was part of \"an ongoing investigation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n==Reuniting with Cheech==\n[[File:Tommy Chong TIFF08.jpg|thumb|Tommy Chong in Toronto, 2008]]\nChong appeared with his long-time comedy partner, [[Cheech Marin]], in a 2000 [[South Park]] episode called \"[[Cherokee Hair Tampons]]\", where they played fictional versions of themselves.\n\nIn mid-2008, [[Cheech & Chong]] reunited and started touring. The tour was called ''Light Up America and Canada'' and ''The Felimony Tour'', which referred to major expenses of each. In October 2008, they appeared on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'' , the ''[[Opie and Anthony]]'' Show,  and the ''[[Ron and Fez]]'' Show on [[Sirius radio|SIRIUS]]/[[XM Satellite Radio]]. On March 1, 2010, they hosted ''[[WWE Raw]]'' in [[Oklahoma City]]. On March 13, 2011, Cheech & Chong were guest stars on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[A Midsummer's Nice Dream]]\", where, during a reunion tour, Homer briefly replaced Chong before the pair reconciled.\n\n[[Cheech Marin]] appeared in Tommy Chong's first dance in the season opener of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', on September 15, 2014. Around this same time, Cheech and Chong appeared together on the internet-based, pro-marijuana show, [[Getting Doug With High]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1960, Chong married Maxine Sneed in Canada. She is of [[Black Canadian]] and [[Cherokee]] descent. They have two daughters, [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]] (b. 1961) and [[Robbi Chong]] (b. 1965). They divorced in 1970.\n\nIn 1975, Chong married [[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]] in Los Angeles. They had three children, sons Paris (b. 1974) and Gilbran (b. 1981), and daughter Precious Chong (b. 1968). In 1978, the couple adopted [[Marcus Chong|Marcus Wyatt]]. Rae Dawn, Robbi, Marcus, Paris, and Precious Chong have each pursued careers in acting. In addition to film work, in May 2011, Precious Chong had her play, ''Push ...One Mother of a Show,'' produced in Toronto.<ref>[http://bunchfamily.ca/precious-chong-pushes-boundaries/ Meghan Housley, \"Precious Chong Pushes Boundaries\"] ''Bunch'', May 7, 2011, accessed December 8, 2013</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s, Chong became a [[naturalized citizen]] of the United States. Rae Dawn Chong has also become a naturalized U.S. citizen.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nTommy Chong has become a marijuana activist and supports legalizing the plant's use.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> He is a regular contributor to ''[[Cannabis Culture Magazine]]'' and sits on the [[NORML]] (National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws) advisory board.<ref>https://norml.org/advisory-board</ref>\n\n===Cancer diagnosis===\nChong announced on June 9, 2012, that he is battling [[prostate cancer]]. He described the cancer \"as a slow stage one [that I've] had for a long time.\" He said that he had been drug-free for about three years, during which time he began having prostate-related problems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian Tommy Chong fighting prostate cancer|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/09/showbiz/chong-prostate-cancer/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> On July 15, 2012, Chong tweeted that the [[hemp oil]] treatment he'd been using to cure his cancer was effective and that he is \"99% cancer free.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Twitter|title=Tommy Chong|url=https://twitter.com/tommychong}}</ref> However, on June 16, 2015, Chong stated that he had been diagnosed with [[colorectal cancer]] and was \"using cannabis like crazy\" in order to endure the treatment.<ref>http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/tommy-chong-i-have-rectal-cancer-2015176</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Up in Smoke]]''\n|Anthony \"Man\" Stoner\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Also writer, director\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's Next Movie]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Chong\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Nice Dreams]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|''[[It Came from Hollywood]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Things Are Tough All Over]]''\n|Chong / Prince Habib\n|Also writer\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|''[[Still Smokin (film)|Still Smokin']]''\n|Chong\n|Also writer, director\n|-\n|