eb.archive.org/web/20090905063448/http://video.msn.com/video.aspx?mkt=en-ca Video interview with Tommy Chong on 'Connected Life']\n*[http://www.law.uga.edu/profile/donald-e-wilkes-jr Donald E. Wilkes, Jr.], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120314091056/http://www.law.uga.edu/dwilkes_more/55pope.html \"Pot Pope Imprisoned.\"] Published in Flagpole Magazine, p.&nbsp;31 (December 20, 2006).\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Cheech & Chong}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chong, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the cannabis industry]]\n[[Category:Canadian cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ulster-Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic drug advocates]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Writers from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:People convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Victoria School of Performing and Visual Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American film directors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:The Masked Singer (American TV series) contestants]]\n", "name_user": "Miami Jackson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Chong"}
{"title_page": "Michael Green Architecture", "text_new": "'''Michael Green Architecture''' is a Canadian architecture + interior design firm founded in 2012 and located in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Michael Green founded the firm and acts both as the president and CEO of the company. They offer various services from [[landscape architecture]], [[interior design]], renovations, architectural renderings, graphic design and model making.\n\nThe firm is known for its leadership in building with advanced wood products and technologies. A vocal firm concerning [[Engineered wood|mass timber]] construction. Advocating for wood buildings and wood cities since its inception. Designing multiple mass timber structures in North America and teaching on its possibilities.\n\n== History ==\nFounded by award-winning architect Michael Green who is known for his research and advocacy on the use of wood technology in construction. The firm was started a year after Green had split from his old partners at McFarlane Green Biggar Architecture + Design (MGB). With him looking for more diversity and designing projects that had social conscience and environmental impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanmag.com/the-architecture-philosophy-of-michael-green|title=Vancouver Magazine|last=Mckenzie|first=Kevin Hinton & Ryan|website=Vancouver Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Green advocates for greater use of wood in the construction of large buildings to reduce their environmental footprint due to buildings being responsible for a majority of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/881601/vancouver-architect-michael-green-spurs-global-movement-tall-wood-buildings|title=Vancouver architect Michael Green spurs global movement for tall wood buildings|date=2017-03-15|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nPushing the boundaries of mass timber construction and have completed some of the largest timber buildings in the world. First, in 2016, The Wood Innovation Design Centre was completed in Prince George, B.C. At the time, at eight-story and 96-foot-tall, it stood as the tallest building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/detail/innovative-detail-wood-innovation-and-design-centre_o|title=https://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/detail/innovative-detail-wood-innovation-and-design-centre_o|website=www.architectmagazine.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Then in 2017, they designed T3 Minneapolis, a 7-storey, 220,000-square-foot building, which stood as the largest wood building in North America at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://structurecraft.com/projects/t3-minneapolis|title=T3 Minneapolis Office Building {{!}} Mass Timber Office Building|website=StructureCraft Builders|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Michael Green Architecture (MGA) was acquired by [[Katerra]], a Silicon Valley construction start-up which is run by former Tesla interim CEO Michael Marks. Through the acquisition, Katerra purchased 100% of the economic interests in MGA. The voting shares remained majority-owned and controlled by MGA's board of directors and Michael Green remained the president and CEO of the firm. The firm since then has changed its name to Michael Green Architecture, a Katerra company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13471-design-build-giant-katerra-acquires-lord-aeck-sargent-michael-green-architecture?v=preview|title=Design-Build Giant Katerra Acquires Lord Aeck Sargent, Michael Green Architecture|website=www.architecturalrecord.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\nSince the firm's inception in 2012, the firm has completed a wide variety of projects:\n\n=== Academic ===\n\n* Wood Innovation and Design Centre, [[Prince George, British Columbia|Prince George]]\n* OSU College of Forestry, [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]]\n* UBC Baseball, Vancouver\n* Pirurvik Centre, [[Iqaluit]]\n\n=== Airport ===\n\n*[[Prince George Airport]], Prince George\n*[[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa Airport]] Phase 2, [[Ottawa]]\n\n=== Commercial ===\n\n* T3 Minneapolis, [[Minneapolis]]\n* Rennie Gallery, Vancouver\n* Shoreline, Vancouver\n* Lynnsteven, Vancouver\n* The Square - DDB, Vancouver\n* Obakki, Vancouver\n* Kokko, [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]]\n* Matchstick Coffee Roasters, Vancouver\n* Whistler Rendezvous Renovation, [[Blackcomb Peak]]\n\n=== Community ===\n\n*[[Sidewalk Labs]], [[Toronto]]\n* Ronald McDonald House BC, Vancouver\n* North Vancouver City Hall, North Vancouver\n* Aberdeen Dragons, Richmond\n\n=== Office ===\n\n* Interfor \u2013 Burnaby Office, [[Burnaby]]\n\n=== Recreation ===\n\n* The Dock Building, Vancouver\n\n=== Residential ===\n\n* Sixth + Willow, Vancouver\n* Canon Point Residence, Canon Point\n* Accessory Studio, [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver]]\n* Parthenon Place, Vancouver\n* Evergreen Residence, North Vancouver\n\n=== Ongoing ===\n\n* Parkway Building, Victoria\n* Sidewalk Labs, Toronto\n* Honeycomb Housing Prototype, [[Austin, Texas|Austin]]\n* The Scott Building, Victoria\n* OSU College of Forestry, Corvallis\n\n== Awards ==\n\n==== Wood Innovation and Design Centre ====\n\n* 2016 Governor General\u2019s Medal in Architecture\n* 2015 RAIC Award of Excellence for Innovation in Architecture\n* 2015 Lieutenant-Governor of BC Award in Architecture (Merit)\n* 2015 AIBC Innovation Award\n\n==== Prince George Airport ====\n\n* 2006 Lieutenant\u2010Governor of BC Medal\n\n==== T3 Minneapolis ====\n\n* 2017 Wood Design BC, International Wood Design Award\n* 2017 US WoodWorks Wood Design, Special Recognition Award\n* 2017 Minnesota Construction Association Awards of Excellence, Green/Sustainable Project\n* 2017 AZ Awards Winner: Environmental Leadership<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azuremagazine.com/article/2017-az-awards-winner-environmental-leadership/|title=2017 AZ Awards Winner: Environmental Leadership|date=2017-06-23|website=Azure Magazine|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2016 Wood Design & Building, Citation Award\n\n==== Lynnsteven ====\n\n* 2010 IIDA Project of the Year\n* 2010 AIBC Special Jury Award, \u201cFor innovative treatment of interior design with consideration to budgetary constraints\u201d\n\n==== Ronald McDonald House BC ====\n\n* 2016 Governor General\u2019s Award in Architecture\n* 2015 Lieutenant-Governor of BC Award in Architecture (Merit)\n* 2015 Masonry Institute of BC \u2013 Award of Excellence \u2013 Low Rise\n\n==== North Vancouver City Hall ====\n\n* 2014 Governor General\u2019s Award in Architecture\n\n==== The Dock Building ====\n\n* 2018 AIBC Special Jury Award\n\n==== Accessory Studio ====\n\n* 2004 Lieutenant\u2010Governor of BC Merit Award\n\n== Tall Wood Teachings ==\nEducating on the possibilities of wood construction is at the forefront of the firm's goals. Michael Green teaches internationally at various locations, with his TED talk, \u201c[https://www.ted.com/talks/michael_green_why_we_should_build_wooden_skyscrapers?language=en Why We Should Build Wooden Skyscrapers]\u201d, being the most prominent. Green is also the founder of 'Design Build Research (DBR)' and 'Timber Online Education (TOE)', a research platform dedicated to teaching on the design and construction of student led installations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/features/article/139051283/the-school-of-helpful-knocks-the-experiential-pedagogy-of-design-build-research|title=The school of helpful knocks: the experiential pedagogy of Design Build Research|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThey have released a couple books on the subject, enlightening on research done and wood buildings of various typologies built already. In 2012, the firm released the first version of the book 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings' which teaches on structural wood systems and how to make it work by exploring various case studies. In 2019, a second updated version was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/220779/michael-green-presents-the-case-for-tall-wood-buildings/|title=Michael Green presents 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings'|date=2012-03-27|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The second book titled \u2018Tall Wood Buildings: Design, Construction and Performance\u2019 was released in 2017 and co-authored with Jim Taggart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/220779/michael-green-presents-the-case-for-tall-wood-buildings/|title=Michael Green presents 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings'|date=2012-03-27|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Not only does this book touch on architecture on construction but also presents options for building for a more sustainable future.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "'''Michael Green Architecture''' is a Canadian architecture + interior design firm founded in 2012 and located in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Michael Green founded the firm and acts both as the president and CEO of the company. They offer various services from [[landscape architecture]], [[interior design]], renovations, architectural renderings, graphic design and model making.\n\nThe firm is known for its leadership in building with advanced wood products and technologies. A vocal firm concerning [[Engineered wood|mass timber]] construction. Advocating for wood buildings and wood cities since its inception. Designing multiple mass timber structures in North America and teaching on its possibilities.\n\n== History ==\nFounded by award-winning architect Michael Green who is known for his research and advocacy on the use of wood technology in construction. The firm was started a year after Green had split from his old partners at McFarlane Green Biggar Architecture + Design (MGB). With him looking for more diversity and designing projects that had social conscience and environmental impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanmag.com/the-architecture-philosophy-of-michael-green|title=Vancouver Magazine|last=Mckenzie|first=Kevin Hinton & Ryan|website=Vancouver Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Green advocates for greater use of wood in the construction of large buildings to reduce their environmental footprint due to buildings being responsible for a majority of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/news/881601/vancouver-architect-michael-green-spurs-global-movement-tall-wood-buildings|title=Vancouver architect Michael Green spurs global movement for tall wood buildings|date=2017-03-15|website=The Georgia Straight|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \n\nPushing the boundaries of mass timber construction and have completed some of the largest timber buildings in the world. First, in 2016, The Wood Innovation Design Centre was completed in Prince George, B.C. At the time, at eight-story and 96-foot-tall, it stood as the tallest building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/detail/innovative-detail-wood-innovation-and-design-centre_o|title=https://www.architectmagazine.com/technology/detail/innovative-detail-wood-innovation-and-design-centre_o|website=www.architectmagazine.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Then in 2017, they designed T3 Minneapolis, a 7-storey, 220,000-square-foot building, which stood as the largest wood building in North America at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://structurecraft.com/projects/t3-minneapolis|title=T3 Minneapolis Office Building {{!}} Mass Timber Office Building|website=StructureCraft Builders|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2018, Michael Green Architecture (MGA) was acquired by [[Katerra]], a Silicon Valley construction start-up which is run by former Tesla interim CEO Michael Marks. Through the acquisition, Katerra purchased 100% of the economic interests in MGA. The voting shares remained majority-owned and controlled by MGA's board of directors and Michael Green remained the president and CEO of the firm. The firm since then has changed its name to Michael Green Architecture, a Katerra company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/13471-design-build-giant-katerra-acquires-lord-aeck-sargent-michael-green-architecture?v=preview|title=Design-Build Giant Katerra Acquires Lord Aeck Sargent, Michael Green Architecture|website=www.architecturalrecord.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\nSince the firm's inception in 2012, the firm has completed a wide variety of projects:\n\n=== Academic ===\n\n* Wood Innovation and Design Centre, [[Prince George, British Columbia|Prince George]]\n* OSU College of Forestry, [[Corvallis, Oregon|Corvallis]]\n* UBC Baseball, Vancouver\n* Pirurvik Centre, [[Iqaluit]]\n\n=== Airport ===\n\n*[[Prince George Airport]], Prince George\n*[[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Ottawa Airport]] Phase 2, [[Ottawa]]\n\n=== Commercial ===\n\n* T3 Minneapolis, [[Minneapolis]]\n* Rennie Gallery, Vancouver\n* Shoreline, Vancouver\n* Lynnsteven, Vancouver\n* The Square - DDB, Vancouver\n* Obakki, Vancouver\n* Kokko, [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]]\n* Matchstick Coffee Roasters, Vancouver\n* Whistler Rendezvous Renovation, [[Blackcomb Peak]]\n\n=== Community ===\n\n*[[Sidewalk Labs]], [[Toronto]]\n* Ronald McDonald House BC, Vancouver\n* North Vancouver City Hall, North Vancouver\n* Aberdeen Dragons, Richmond\n\n=== Office ===\n\n* Interfor \u2013 Burnaby Office, [[Burnaby]]\n\n=== Recreation ===\n\n* The Dock Building, Vancouver\n\n=== Residential ===\n\n* Sixth + Willow, Vancouver\n* Canon Point Residence, Canon Point\n* Accessory Studio, [[North Vancouver (city)|North Vancouver]]\n* Parthenon Place, Vancouver\n* Evergreen Residence, North Vancouver\n\n=== Ongoing ===\n\n* Parkway Building, Victoria\n* Sidewalk Labs, Toronto\n* Honeycomb Housing Prototype, [[Austin, Texas|Austin]]\n* The Scott Building, Victoria\n* OSU College of Forestry, Corvallis\n\n== Awards ==\n\n==== Wood Innovation and Design Centre ====\n\n* 2016 Governor General\u2019s Medal in Architecture\n* 2015 RAIC Award of Excellence for Innovation in Architecture\n* 2015 Lieutenant-Governor of BC Award in Architecture (Merit)\n* 2015 AIBC Innovation Award\n\n==== Prince George Airport ====\n\n* 2006 Lieutenant\u2010Governor of BC Medal\n\n==== T3 Minneapolis ====\n\n* 2017 Wood Design BC, International Wood Design Award\n* 2017 US WoodWorks Wood Design, Special Recognition Award\n* 2017 Minnesota Construction Association Awards of Excellence, Green/Sustainable Project\n* 2017 AZ Awards Winner: Environmental Leadership<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azuremagazine.com/article/2017-az-awards-winner-environmental-leadership/|title=2017 AZ Awards Winner: Environmental Leadership|date=2017-06-23|website=Azure Magazine|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2016 Wood Design & Building, Citation Award\n\n==== Lynnsteven ====\n\n* 2010 IIDA Project of the Year\n* 2010 AIBC Special Jury Award, \u201cFor innovative treatment of interior design with consideration to budgetary constraints\u201d\n\n==== Ronald McDonald House BC ====\n\n* 2016 Governor General\u2019s Award in Architecture\n* 2015 Lieutenant-Governor of BC Award in Architecture (Merit)\n* 2015 Masonry Institute of BC \u2013 Award of Excellence \u2013 Low Rise\n\n==== North Vancouver City Hall ====\n\n* 2014 Governor General\u2019s Award in Architecture\n\n==== The Dock Building ====\n\n* 2018 AIBC Special Jury Award\n\n==== Accessory Studio ====\n\n* 2004 Lieutenant\u2010Governor of BC Merit Award\n\n== Tall Wood Teachings ==\nEducating on the possibilities of wood construction is at the forefront of the firm's goals. Michael Green teaches internationally at various locations, with his TED talk, \u201c[https://www.ted.com/talks/michael_green_why_we_should_build_wooden_skyscrapers?language=en Why We Should Build Wooden Skyscrapers]\u201d, being the most prominent. Green is also the founder of 'Design Build Research (DBR)' and 'Timber Online Education (TOE)', a research platform dedicated to teaching on the design and construction of student led installations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archinect.com/features/article/139051283/the-school-of-helpful-knocks-the-experiential-pedagogy-of-design-build-research|title=The school of helpful knocks: the experiential pedagogy of Design Build Research|website=Archinect|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThey have released a couple books on the subject, enlightening on research done and wood buildings of various typologies built already. In 2012, the firm released the first version of the book 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings' which teaches on structural wood systems and how to make it work by exploring various case studies. In 2019, a second updated version was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/220779/michael-green-presents-the-case-for-tall-wood-buildings/|title=Michael Green presents 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings'|date=2012-03-27|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The second book titled \u2018Tall Wood Buildings: Design, Construction and Performance\u2019 was released in 2017 and co-authored with Jim Taggart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/220779/michael-green-presents-the-case-for-tall-wood-buildings/|title=Michael Green presents 'The Case for Tall Wood Buildings'|date=2012-03-27|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Not only does this book touch on architecture on construction but also presents options for building for a more sustainable future.\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Green_Architecture"}
{"title_page": "Los Pikadientes de Caborca", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Los Pikadientes de Caborca\n| image                 = \n| caption            = \n| image_size            = 200px\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Caborca]], [[Sonora]], [[Mexico]]\n| genre               = [[Cumbia]],[[Norte\u00f1o (music)|Norte\u00f1o]], [[Latin pop]]\n| years_active        = 2008 \u2013 Present\n| label               = [[Sony BMG]], Remolino Publishing\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = http://lospikadientes.com/\n| current_members     = Gonzalez Francisco, Gonzalez Javier, Bernabe Leonardo, Nicolas Costich, Neyoy Job \n| past_members        = Chamolo\n}}\n\n'''Los Pikadientes de Caborca''' are a [[Mexico|Mexican]] musical group whose debut single, \"La Cumbia del R\u00edo,\" charted on the [[Hot Latin Tracks|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Tracks]] in 2008.\n\nLos Pikadientes de Caborca began as a [[YouTube]] sensation, with many users posting [[viral video]]s of themselves dancing to the hit.<ref>{{Allmusic | last = Birchmeier | first = Jason | label = Biography of Los Pikadientes de Caborca | id = p1075267 | tab = biography | accessdate = 2008-10-10 }}</ref> [[Sony BMG]] signed the group in 2008 and released their full-length album, ''[[V\u00e1monos Pa'l R\u00edo]]''. The album peaked at #52 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p1075267 | tab = charts-awards/billboard-albums | label = Billboard Albums for Los Pikadientes de Caborca }}</ref> The band received a Grammy nomination for Best Regional Mexican Album at the [[2009 Grammy Awards]]. and they Show debut was in front of 200 thousand people in Whittier Narrows Park.\n\n[[Francisco Gonz\u00e1lez]] In 2014, he won the Composer of the Year award for Monitor Latino, other nominations include the Billboard Awards, Lo Nuestro Awards and the Grammys.\n\n[[Francisco Gonz\u00e1lez]] continued to write songs for other artists, in 2019 he reunited the band and in 2020, Francisco participated in Fashion Week in New York and debuted on the catwalk with Alonso M\u00e1ximo's designer . They are currently finishing the recording of their next album, which is expected to be released in late May 2020.\n\nFrancisco Gonz\u00e1lez is the first voice of the band, Sonoran, red-bone musician, composer and founder of Los Pikadientes. He has composed songs for some groups such as [[Calibre 50]], [[Banda Los Recoditos]], La # 1 Banda Jerez De Marcos Flores, Julion Alvarez, Saul El Jaguar, Chuy Lizarraga and La Original Banda Lim\u00f3n.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* 2008: ''[[V\u00e1monos Pa'l R\u00edo]]''\n* 2009: ''[[La Ten\u00eda M\u00e1s Grande]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Mas Desmadrosos Que Nunca]]''\n\n===Singles===\n* 2008: \"La Cumbia del R\u00edo\"\n\n==Awards==\n;2009\n*[[51st Grammy Awards|Grammy Awards]]\n**Best Regional Mexican Album [Nominated]\n*[[Premios Lo Nuestro 2009|Lo Nuestro Awards]]\n** Breakout Artist or Group of the Year [Nominated]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?chid%3D10383%26schid%3D10646%26secid%3D10648%26cid%3D1794883 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313150858/http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?chid=10383&schid=10646&secid=10648&cid=1794883 |archivedate=2009-03-13 }}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n* January 2008: ''[[Gonzalez Terrazas Francisco Rafael (Singer)]]\n* January 2011: ''[[Gonzalez Gastelum Javier Alberto (Saxofon) ]]\t\n* April 2018: ''[[Neyoy Ruiz Job Esteban (Baterista)]]\n* May 2018: ''[[Bernabe Roman Leonardo (Tuba)]]\n* January 2019: ''[[Nicolas Costich Costich (Guitarr)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://myspace.com/lospikadientesdecaborca Los Pikadientes de Caborca] on [[Myspace]] (Official)\n* {{youtube|user=pikadientesdecaborca}} (