{"title_page": "Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| image       = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky.jpg\n| alt         = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| caption     = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = German hymnwriter\n| birth_date  = {{start-date|September 7, 1690|mf=yes}}\n| death_date  = {{Death-date and age|June 15, 1774|September 7, 1690|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Jankowe]], [[Lower Silesia]]\n| death_place = \n}}\n\n'''Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky''' ([[Jankowe]], [[Lower Silesia]] September 7, 1690 \u2013 June 15, 1774) was a [[Germany|German]] hymn writer.\n\n==Life==\nAt first a page at the ducal court of Saxe-Weissenfels, he next studied law and [[theology]] at [[Jena]] and [[University of Halle|Halle]]; but ill health prevented his preferment. He settled at [[Glaucha]] in [[Silesia]], now part of [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]], where he founded an [[orphanage]]. After living for a time at [[K\u00f6stritz]], and from 1740 to 1745 at the court of [[Christian Ernest II, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld|Christian Ernst]], duke of Saxe-Coburg, at Saalfeld, he made his home at the Waisenhaus (orphanage) at Halle, where, until his death, he engaged in spiritual work and in composing hymns and sacred songs.\n\n==Works==\n[[File:G\u00fcldenes Schatz-K\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes - 28. Aufl., Halle, 1772.jpg|thumb|left|''G\u00fcldenes Schatz-K\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes'', 28th edition 1772]]\nBogatzky's main works are ''G\u00fcldenes Schatzk\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes'' (Little Golden Treasure Chest of God's Children, 1718) and ''\u00dcbung der Gottseligkeit in allerlei geistlichen Liedern'' (Exercises Regarding God's Blessedness in All Forms of Religious Songs, 1750). He also wrote A Golden Treasury for the Children of God in 1746; this was one of the favourite books of [[Jane Gardiner]] (1758-1840), an English school owner.<ref name=\"EAGardiner\">{{cite book|last1=Gardiner|first1= Everilda|title=Recollections of a Beloved Mother|date=1842|publisher=E.A. Gardiner|url=https://archive.org/details/recollectionsab00gardgoog}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Bogatzky, Karl Heinrich von}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://members.optushome.com.au/kswans/bogatzky.html   Further information]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bogatzky, Karl Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:1690 births]]\n[[Category:1774 deaths]]\n[[Category:German songwriters]]\n[[Category:German Lutheran hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Silesian Voivodeship]]\n\n\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| image       = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky.jpg\n| alt         = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| caption     = Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky\n| other_names = \n| occupation  = German hymnwriter\n| birth_date  = {{start-date|September 7, 1690|mf=yes}}\n| death_date  = {{Death-date and age|June 15, 1774|September 7, 1690|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Jankowe]], [[Lower Silesia]]\n| death_place = \n}}\n\n'''Karl Heinrich von Bogatzky''' ([[Jankowe]], [[Lower Silesia]] September 7, 1690 \u2013 June 15, 1774) was a [[Germany|German]] hymn writer.\n\n==Life==\nAt first a page at the ducal court of Saxe-Weissenfels, he next studied law and [[theology]] at [[Jena]] and [[University of Halle|Halle]]; but ill health prevented his preferment. He settled at [[Glaucha]] in [[Silesia]], now part of [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]], where he founded an [[orphanage]]. After living for a time at [[K\u00f6stritz]], and from 1740 to 1745 at the court of [[Christian Ernest II, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld|Christian Ernst]], duke of Saxe-Coburg, at Saalfeld, he made his home at the Waisenhaus (orphanage) at Halle, where, until his death, he engaged in spiritual work and in composing hymns and sacred songs.\n\n==Works==\n[[File:G\u00fcldenes Schatz-K\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes - 28. Aufl., Halle, 1772.jpg|thumb|left|''G\u00fcldenes Schatz-K\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes'', 28th edition 1772]]\nBogatzky's main works are ''G\u00fcldenes Schatzk\u00e4stlein der Kinder Gottes'' (Little Golden Treasure Chest of God's Children, 1718) and ''\u00dcbung der Gottseligkeit in allerlei geistlichen Liedern'' (Exercises Regarding God's Blessedness in All Forms of Religious Songs, 1750). He also wrote A Golden Treasury for the Children of God in 1746; this was one of the favourite books of [[Jane Gardiner]] (1758-1840), an English school owner.<ref name=\"EAGardiner\">{{cite book|last1=Gardiner|first1= Everilda|title=Recollections of a Beloved Mother|date=1842|publisher=E.A. Gardiner|url=https://archive.org/details/recollectionsab00gardgoog}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Bogatzky, Karl Heinrich von}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://members.optushome.com.au/kswans/bogatzky.html   Further information]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bogatzky, Karl Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:1690 births]]\n[[Category:1774 deaths]]\n[[Category:German songwriters]]\n[[Category:German Lutheran hymnwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Silesian Voivodeship]]\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Heinrich_von_Bogatzky"}
